				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Dim=
ension of the column space of a matrix</div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra" title=3D"Lin=
ear algebra">linear algebra</a>, the <b>rank</b> of a <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics)" title=3D"Matrix (mathematics)">ma=
trix</a> <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>=
 is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimension_(vector_space)" =
title=3D"Dimension (vector space)">dimension</a> of the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_space" title=3D"Vector space">vector space</a>=
 generated (or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_span" title=
=3D"Linear span">spanned</a>) by its columns.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rank_(linear_algebr=
a)#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_2-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rank_(linear_algebra)#cite_note-:0-=
2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rank_(linear_algebra)#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This co=
rresponds to the maximal number of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Linearly_independent" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Linearly independent"=
>linearly independent</a> columns of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">A</span>. This, in turn, is identical to the dimension =
of the vector space spanned by its rows.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-mackiw_4-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rank_(linear_alge=
bra)#cite_note-mackiw-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Rank is thus a measure of the "<a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Degenerate_form" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Degenerate form">nondegenerateness</a>" of the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_of_linear_equations" title=3D"System of linear e=
quations">system of linear equations</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Linear_transformation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Linear tra=
nsformation">linear transformation</a> encoded by <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>. There are multiple equivalent de=
finitions of rank. A matrix's rank is one of its most fundamental character=
istics.
</p><p>The rank is commonly denoted by <span class=3D"texhtml">rank(<i>A</i=
>)</span> or <span class=3D"texhtml">rk(<i>A</i>)</span>;<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-:0_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rank=
_(linear_algebra)#cite_note-:0-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> sometimes the parentheses are =
not written, as in <span class=3D"texhtml">rank <i>A</i></span>.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ra=
nk_(linear_algebra)#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>i<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Main_definitions">Main defi=
nitions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRank=
_(linear_algebra)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Main definitions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<p>In this section, we give some definitions of the rank of a matrix.  Many=
 definitions are possible; see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ran=
k_(linear_algebra)#Alternative_definitions">Alternative definitions</a> for=
 several of these.
</p><p>The <b>column rank</b> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font=
-style:italic;">A</span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Di=
mension_(linear_algebra)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dimension (linear =
algebra)">dimension</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Col=
umn_space" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Column space">column space</a> of=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>, while =
the <b>row rank</b> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">A</span> is the dimension of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Row_space" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Row space">row space</a> of =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>.
</p><p>A fundamental result in linear algebra is that the column rank and t=
he row rank are always equal. (Three proofs of this result are given in <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rank_(linear_algebra)#Proofs_that_col=
umn_rank_=3D_row_rank">=C2=A7&nbsp;Proofs that column rank =3D row rank</a>=
, below.)  This number (i.e., the number of linearly independent rows or co=
lumns) is simply called the <b>rank</b> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" sty=
le=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>.
</p><p>A matrix is said to have <b>full rank</b> if its rank equals the lar=
gest possible for a matrix of the same dimensions, which is the lesser of t=
he number of rows and columns.  A matrix is said to be <b>rank-deficient</b=
> if it does not have full rank. The <b>rank deficiency</b> of a matrix is =
the difference between the lesser of the number of rows and columns, and th=
e rank.
</p><p>The rank of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_map" t=
itle=3D"Linear map">linear map</a> or operator <span class=3D"mwe-math-elem=
ent mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math=
-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/199=
