<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Computation">Computation</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRank_(linear_a=
lgebra)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Computati=
on"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p>When applied to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floating_point"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Floating point">floating point</a> computat=
ions on computers, basic Gaussian elimination (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/LU_decomposition" title=3D"LU decomposition">LU decomposition<=
/a>) can be unreliable, and a rank-revealing decomposition should be used i=
nstead. An effective alternative is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Singular_value_decomposition" title=3D"Singular value decomposition">=
singular value decomposition</a> (SVD), but there are other less computatio=
nally expensive choices, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Q=
R_decomposition" title=3D"QR decomposition">QR decomposition</a> with pivot=
ing (so-called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rank-revealing_QR_f=
actorization" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rank-revealing QR factorizatio=
n">rank-revealing QR factorization</a>), which are still more numerically r=
obust than Gaussian elimination. Numerical determination of rank requires a=
 criterion for deciding when a value, such as a singular value from the SVD=
, should be treated as zero, a practical choice which depends on both the m=
atrix and the application.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Proofs_that_column_rank_=3D=
_row_rank"><span id=3D"Proofs_that_column_rank_.3D_row_rank"></span>Proofs =
that column rank =3D row rank</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DRank_(linear_algebra)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" =
title=3D"Edit section: Proofs that column rank =3D row rank"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Proof_using_row_reduction">=
Proof using row reduction</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DRank_(linear_algebra)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" titl=
e=3D"Edit section: Proof using row reduction"><span>edit</span></a><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The fact that the column and row ranks of any matrix are equal is fundam=
ental in linear algebra. Many proofs have been given. One of the most eleme=
ntary ones has been sketched in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ra=
nk_(linear_algebra)#Rank_from_row_echelon_forms">=C2=A7&nbsp;Rank from row =
echelon forms</a>. Here is a variant of this proof:
</p><p>It is straightforward to show that neither the row rank nor the colu=
mn rank are changed by an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elementa=
ry_row_operation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Elementary row operation">=
elementary row operation</a>. As <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G=
aussian_elimination" title=3D"Gaussian elimination">Gaussian elimination</a=
> proceeds by elementary row operations, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Reduced_row_echelon_form" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Reduced=
 row echelon form">reduced row echelon form</a> of a matrix has the same ro=
w rank and the same column rank as the original matrix. Further elementary =
column operations allow putting the matrix in the form of an <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Identity_matrix" title=3D"Identity matrix">ident=
ity matrix</a> possibly bordered by rows and columns of zeros. Again, this =
changes neither the row rank nor the column rank. It is immediate that both=
 the row and column ranks of this resulting matrix is the number of its non=
zero entries.
</p><p>We present two other proofs of this result. The first uses only basi=
c properties of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_combination=
" title=3D"Linear combination">linear combinations</a> of vectors, and is v=
alid over any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_(mathematics)"=
 title=3D"Field (mathematics)">field</a>. The proof is based upon Wardlaw (=
2005).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-wardlaw_10-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rank_(linear_algebra)#cite_note-wardlaw-10"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> The second uses <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthogonalit=
y" title=3D"Orthogonality">orthogonality</a> and is valid for matrices over=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_numbers" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Real numbers">real numbers</a>; it is based upon Mackiw (19=
95).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-mackiw_4-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rank_(linear_algebra)#cite_note-mackiw-4"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
Both proofs can be found in the book by Banerjee and Roy (2014).<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-banerjee-roy_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Rank_(linear_algebra)#cite_note-banerjee-roy-11"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Proof_using_linear_combinat=
ions">Proof using linear combinations</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DRank_(linear_algebra)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;secti=
on=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Proof using linear combinations"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Let <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> b=
e an <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i> =C3=97 <i>n</i></span> matrix. Let th=
e column rank of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
A</span> be <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</sp=
an>, and let <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>c</b><sub>1</sub>, ..., <b>c</b><su=
b><i>r</i></sub></span> be any basis for the column space of <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>. Place these as the co=
lumns of an <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i> =C3=97 <i>r</i></span> matrix =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">C</span>. Every c=
olumn of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>=
 can be expressed as a linear combination of the <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> columns in <span class=3D"texhtml =
mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">C</span>. This means that there is an <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i> =C3=97 <i>n</i></span> matrix <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">R</span> such that <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i> =3D <i>CR</i></span>. <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">R</span> is the matrix whose <span class=3D"texh=
tml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">i</span>th column is formed from the=
 coefficients giving the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">i</span>th column of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">A</span> as a linear combination of the <span class=3D"texhtml =
mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> columns of <span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">C</span>. In other words, <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">R</span> is the matrix which=
 contains the multiples for the bases of the column space of <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> (which is <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">C</span>), which are then us=
ed to form <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</spa=
n> as a whole. Now, each row of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-=
style:italic;">A</span> is given by a linear combination of the <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> rows of <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">R</span>. Therefore, the row=
s of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">R</span> for=
m a spanning set of the row space of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">A</span> and, by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Steinitz_exchange_lemma" title=3D"Steinitz exchange lemma">Steinitz =
exchange lemma</a>, the row rank of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">A</span> cannot exceed <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" styl=
e=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span>. This proves that the row rank of <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> is less than or=
 equal to the column rank of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">A</span>. This result can be applied to any matrix, so apply th=
e result to the transpose of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">A</span>. Since the row rank of the transpose of <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> is the column rank of =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> and the =
column rank of the transpose of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-=
style:italic;">A</span> is the row rank of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" sty=
le=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>, this establishes the reverse inequality=
 and we obtain the equality of the row rank and the column rank of <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>. (Also see <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rank_factorization" title=3D"Rank facto=
rization">Rank factorization</a>.)
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Proof_using_orthogonality">=
Proof using orthogonality</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DRank_(linear_algebra)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" titl=
e=3D"Edit section: Proof using orthogonality"><span>edit</span></a><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Let <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> b=
e an <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i>=E2=80=89=C3=97=E2=80=89<i>n</i></span=
