n"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRank_(linear_algebra)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;=
section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Determinantal rank =E2=80=93 size of l=
argest non-vanishing minor"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The rank of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A<=
/span> is the largest order of any non-zero <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Minor_(linear_algebra)" title=3D"Minor (linear algebra)">minor</a=
> in <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>.  (=
The order of a minor is the side-length of the square sub-matrix of which i=
t is the determinant.) Like the decomposition rank characterization, this d=
oes not give an efficient way of computing the rank, but it is useful theor=
etically: a single non-zero minor witnesses a lower bound (namely its order=
) for the rank of the matrix, which can be useful (for example) to prove th=
at certain operations do not lower the rank of a matrix.
</p><p>A non-vanishing <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">p</span>-minor (<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i> =C3=97 <i>p</i></spa=
n> submatrix with non-zero determinant) shows that the rows and columns of =
that submatrix are linearly independent, and thus those rows and columns of=
 the full matrix are linearly independent (in the full matrix), so the row =
and column rank are at least as large as the determinantal rank; however, t=
he converse is less straightforward.  The equivalence of determinantal rank=
 and column rank is a strengthening of the statement that if the span of <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> vectors ha=
s dimension <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</sp=
an>, then <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span=
> of those vectors span the space (equivalently, that one can choose a span=
ning set that is a <i>subset</i> of the vectors): the equivalence implies t=
hat a subset of the rows and a subset of the columns simultaneously define =
an invertible submatrix (equivalently, if the span of <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> vectors has dimension <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span>, then <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span> of these vectors =
span the space <i>and</i> there is a set of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span> coordinates on which they are linearly =
independent).
</p>
