<p>One useful application of calculating the rank of a matrix is the comput=
ation of the number of solutions of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/System_of_linear_equations" title=3D"System of linear equations">system=
 of linear equations</a>. According to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Rouch%C3%A9%E2%80%93Capelli_theorem" title=3D"Rouch=C3=A9=E2=80=93=
Capelli theorem">Rouch=C3=A9=E2=80=93Capelli theorem</a>, the system is inc=
onsistent if the rank of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Augme=
nted_matrix" title=3D"Augmented matrix">augmented matrix</a> is greater tha=
n the rank of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coefficient_matr=
ix" title=3D"Coefficient matrix">coefficient matrix</a>. If on the other ha=
nd, the ranks of these two matrices are equal, then the system must have at=
 least one solution. The solution is unique if and only if the rank equals =
the number of variables. Otherwise the general solution has <span class=3D"=
texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> free parameters where <=
span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> is the di=
fference between the number of variables and the rank.  In this case (and a=
ssuming the system of equations is in the real or complex numbers) the syst=
em of equations has infinitely many solutions.
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Control_theory" title=3D=
"Control theory">control theory</a>, the rank of a matrix can be used to de=
termine whether a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_system" t=
itle=3D"Linear system">linear system</a> is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Controllability" title=3D"Controllability">controllable</a>, or <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Observability" title=3D"Observabili=
ty">observable</a>.
</p><p>In the field of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Communicati=
on_complexity" title=3D"Communication complexity">communication complexity<=
/a>, the rank of the communication matrix of a function gives bounds on the=
 amount of communication needed for two parties to compute the function.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Generalization">Generalizat=
ion</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRank_(li=
near_algebra)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit section: Ge=
neralization"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p>There are different generalizations of the concept of rank to matrices o=
ver arbitrary <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_(mathematics)" =
title=3D"Ring (mathematics)">rings</a>, where column rank, row rank, dimens=
ion of column space, and dimension of row space of a matrix may be differen=
t from the others or may not exist.
</p><p>Thinking of matrices as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ten=
sors" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tensors">tensors</a>, the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tensor_rank" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Te=
nsor rank">tensor rank</a> generalizes to arbitrary tensors; for tensors of=
 order greater than 2 (matrices are order 2 tensors), rank is very hard to =
compute, unlike for matrices.
</p><p>There is a notion of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rank_(=
differential_topology)" title=3D"Rank (differential topology)">rank</a> for=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smooth_map" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Smooth map">smooth maps</a> between <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Smooth_manifold" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Smooth manifold=
">smooth manifolds</a>. It is equal to the linear rank of the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pushforward_(differential)" title=3D"Pushforwar=
d (differential)">derivative</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Matrices_as_tensors">Matric=
es as tensors</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DRank_(linear_algebra)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit =
section: Matrices as tensors"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Matrix rank should not be confused with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Tensor_order" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tensor order">tensor =
order</a>, which is called tensor rank. Tensor order is the number of indic=
es required to write a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tensor" tit=
le=3D"Tensor">tensor</a>, and thus matrices all have tensor order 2. More p=
recisely, matrices are tensors of type (1,1), having one row index and one =
column index, also called covariant order 1 and contravariant order 1; see =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tensor_(intrinsic_definition)" tit=
le=3D"Tensor (intrinsic definition)">Tensor (intrinsic definition)</a> for =
details.
</p><p>The tensor rank of a matrix can also mean the minimum number of <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_tensor" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Simple tensor">simple tensors</a> necessary to express the matrix a=
s a linear combination, and that this definition does agree with matrix ran=
k as here discussed.
</p>
